<p>
At least ActiveX software used in authentication certificates is on its way to deprecation. The fact that this change was caused by external shocks, including the iPhone, leaves a bitter aftertaste—but it is a good thing nevertheless. #mail also seems to have lost whatever momentum it had; a <a target="_blank" href="http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/09/20/0200000000AKR20150920025500017.HTML">2015 inspection</a> showed that it had only reached 0.02% of its projected usage, including 569 emails sent by individuals not affiliated with the government from January through September 2015. It seems that the service is promoted during mandatory reserve forces training sessions. Hopefully i-PIN will also eventually stop being used.
</p>

<p>
The post-9/11 increase of airport security measures was criticized as security theater, in that it led to excessive intrusion of privacy but was questionable in its effectiveness. In Korea, security theater rules the internet. This theater stages not only security, but also official authentication, convenience and efficacy. Excessive performances for avoiding administrator responsibility, disputes and collusions over privileges and incompetence cover web interfaces like fingerprints. 
</p>

<p>
Recently I was communicating with a Korean local government for a web design project, and got my hands on a document named “<a href="http://opengov.seoul.go.kr/sanction/7348148?fileIdx=1#pdfview">Public and Government Website Development and Management Guidelines for Developers and Administrators.</a>” It specifies that websites need to “remove insecure and non-standard technologies such as ActiveX and NPAPI plugins, and instead apply web standard technologies such as HTML5.” I am unsure when this requirement made its way into the guideline, or why KISA’s website fails to adhere to it. Still, this is a welcome change. It seems that the <a target="_blank" href="https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%EA%B0%88%EB%9D%BC%ED%8C%8C%EA%B3%A0%EC%8A%A4%ED%99%94">Korean Internet Galapagos</a> might soon become past.
</p>

<p>
But on the other hand, the Government i-PIN started to mandate two-factor authentication since June 2016, for “better security.” This was implemented using a ‘graphic authentication’ interface, created by Dementor; while the only reasonable explanation seems to be that it was designed to be as complicated as possible, the company is promoting the interface as “simple and convenient.” This company was selected in K-Global 300, an award hosted by the Ministry of Science, ICT and Future Planning for producing new values in the Creative Economy initiative; it also supplies its product to financial, military and educational sectors. So perhaps the Internet Galapagos is here to stay, after all. This ad by Dementor for their graphic authentication solution seems to be just <a href="/lists/3-seconds" data-permalink="3-seconds" class="list-link">the adequate expression</a> of this depressing prospect.</p>


